SIMPLE: shale
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shale
<hw>Shale</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>scealy</ets>,
<ets>scalu</ets>. See <er>Scalme</er>, and cf. <er>Shell</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A shell or husk; a cod or pod.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The green
<xex>shales</xex> of a bean.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[G. <ets>shale</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>
<def>A fine-grained sedimentary rock of a thin, laminated, and often
friable, structure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bituminous shale</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Bituminous</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shale
<hw>Shale</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To take off the shell or coat of;
to shell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Life, in its upper grades, was bursting its shell, or was
<qex>shaling</qex> off its husk.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shall</ent>⟦br⟧
